=E2=80=9CThis is the entire essence of life: Who are you? What are you?=E2=
=80=9D So proclaimed Leo Tolstoy in the diaries of his youth (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2015/01/28/leo-tolstoy-irina-paperno-self/?utm_source=3D=
Brain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_med=
ium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D07=
3a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CI: how firm a letter; how reassuri=
ng the three strokes: one vertical=2C proud and assertive=2C and then the=
 two short horizontal lines in quick=2C smug succession=2C=E2=80=9D eighte=
en-year-old Sylvia Plath marveled in her own diary a century after Tolstoy=
 as she contemplated free will and what makes us who we are (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2015/10/27/sylvia-plath-journals-privilege-free-will/?utm=
_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_=
29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&m=
c_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Indeed=2C these three smug lines=
 slice through the core of our experience as human beings=2C and yet when=
 we begin to dismantle them=2C we begin to lose sight of that core=2C of t=
he essence of life. What=2C then=2C are we made of? What=2C then=2C makes=
