Needleman writes:

Among the great questions of the human heart=2C none is more central than=
 the question=2C =E2=80=9CWho am I?=E2=80=9D And among the great answers o=
f the human spirit=2C none is more central than the experience of =E2=80=
=9CI Am.=E2=80=9D In fact=2C in the course of an intensely lived human lif=
e =E2=80=94 a normal human life filled with the search for Truth =E2=80=94=
 this question and this answer eventually run parallel to each other=2C co=
ming closer and closer together until the question becomes the answer and=
 the answer becomes the question.

Needleman first confronted this question when he was eleven years old=2C t=
hanks to a neighborhood boy named Elias Barkhordian=2C who became his dear=
est childhood friend and most indefatigable comrade in intellectual inquir=
y. The two would sit together after school for hours on end=2C discussing=
 astronomy and spirituality with equal rigor of openhearted curiosity. But=
 it was Elias=E2=80=99s untimely death=2C as much as his short life=2C tha=
t catapulted Needleman=E2=80=99s existential puzzlements into new heights=
 of understanding. More than half a century later=2C he writes:

Elias died from leukemia=2C at that time incurable=2C just before his four=
teenth birthday. In the months that followed the onset of his illness=2C I=
 would meet with him in the quiet music room at the back of his house=2C f=
acing a large=2C carefully tended=2C sunshine-filled garden. As his illnes=
s progressed and he grew weaker=2C my feeling about his mind deepened. He=
 spoke openly about what awaited him and regretted only that he would not=
 live long enough to understand everything that he wished to understand ab=
out the universe. But somehow=2C doubtless because of the more frequent ap=
pearance in us of shared conscious presence=2C his death eventually=2C in=
 the years that followed=2C brought me more hope than grief=2C the hope th=
at arises from the =E2=80=9Csound=E2=80=9D of a truly sacred consciousness=
 calling to us from within ourselves.

I see now that it is the intimation of this quality of hope that I have al=
l along been trying to bring both to myself and to my students and readers=
 in the face of the illusory hopes and inevitable pessimism so characteris=
tic of our era.

To explore these questions=2C Needleman structures the book in the classic=
 style of a Socratic dialogue=2C but modernizes and enlivens the form with=
 the imaginative twist of staging a conversation between his childhood sel=
f=2C Jerry=2C and his present 80-year-old self=2C Jacob. I am reminded her=
e of Joan Didion=E2=80=99s memorable quip that =E2=80=9Cwe are well advise=
d to keep on nodding terms with the people we used to be=2C whether we fin=
d them attractive company or not=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2=
012/11/19/joan-didion-on-keeping-a-notebook/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&u=
tm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_=
term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 advice often difficult to implement as we wince at=
 the petulance=2C foolishness=2C and hubris of our former selves=2C yet so=
mething Needleman accomplishes with tremendous grace=2C warmth=2C and gene=
rosity of spirit toward the imperfect=2C impatient boy he once was.

Jacob Needleman (Photograph: David Ulrich)

In one of these exchanges=2C Jacob articulates to Jerry the central premis=
e of the book itself:

The struggle to exist=2C to not disappear in this moment=2C is the advanci=
ng root of the struggle to exist throughout the whole passage of time. We=
 need to help each other in this struggle. You by asking=2C I by strugglin=
g to respond. This is the law of love=2C which rules the universe.

In another=2C reminiscent of Alfred Kazin=E2=80=99s beautiful case for emb=
racing contradiction (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/20/alfred-kazi=
n-journals-perception-contradiction/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campa=
ign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0=
_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) =2C Jacob exhorts Jerry:

Stay with the contradiction. If you stay=2C you will see that there is alw=
ays something more than two opposing truths. The whole truth always includ=
es a third part=2C which is the reconciliation.

The willingness to sit with contradiction=2C Needleman argues=2C is the be=
ginning of true self-knowledge and of the deepest kind of truthfulness. Ec=
hoing Andr=C3=A9 Gide=E2=80=99s assertion that sincerity is the most diffi=
cult feat of all (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/13/andre-gide-jour=
nals-sincerity/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAI=
L_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a=
0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Jacob tells=
 Jerry:

This is the beginning of sincerity.

Because you are struggling=2C your question begins to deepen=E2=80=A6 What=
 you will discover=2C always for the first time=2C always new=2C in the fl=
eeting moment of wonder =E2=80=94 before that moment is captured by the am=
bitions of personality. You=2C I=2C in that moment=2C will discover the ne=
ed to serve the energy=2C uniquely human and also sacred=2C that starts as=
 the pure awareness of one=E2=80=99s own existence. And even as this idea=
 =E2=80=94 this beginning idea =E2=80=94 of what is human=2C even as this=
 idea of what is man=2C begins to appear =E2=80=94 even in that fleeting m=
oment of the pure awareness of my existence given now by a great idea =E2=
=80=94 in that moment in front of a living idea=2C an awakening idea=2C a=
 glimpse appears of the uniquely human yearning to serve; the need appears=
=2C the need to obey that energy=2C the need to attend to it=2C to be nour=
ished by it=2C to receive the help that comes then and only then=2C when y=
ou are objectively obliged to give=2C to serve=2C to manifest that energy=
 in action and understanding. It is only that energy
of conscious existence that gives you=2C a human being=2C real strength. T=
he energy that is the total awareness of one=E2=80=99s own existence is=
 =E2=80=94 or can become=2C can be =E2=80=94 the strongest energy in human=
 life.

In another exchange=2C Jacob steers Jerry toward the idea that acknowledgi=
ng the illusoriness of free will liberates us rather than taking away our=
 freedom (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/25/sam-harris-free-will/?u=
tm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_1=
0_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249=
&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Pointing out how impossible it=
 is to understand freedom without understanding the influences acting upon=
 us=2C the laws of the universe=2C and the nature of reality=2C he conside=
rs the source of real freedom:

Ask yourself what is your understanding of the influences acting upon us=
 =E2=80=94 of the universal laws in nature? What are your thoughts about t=
hat? And the teachings of religion =E2=80=94 the idea of faith=2C obedienc=
e to the higher=2C responsibility for others and oneself=2C the deceptions=
 and revelations of sleep and dreaming=2C the very idea of man=E2=80=99s p=
lace in the living=2C breathing=2C sentient cosmos=2C our place on our pla=
net=2C the demand for morality=2C the nature of animal instinct and intuit=
ion within us and around us=2C the function and the meaning of pain and pl=
easure=2C the idea and the experience of consciousness and conscience=2C t=
he subtle nourishment in the air we breathe=2C the food we eat=2C the genu=
ine and the fabricated needs and desires of the body=2C the powerful influ=
ences of symbols=2C the cosmic and intimate force of sex=2C the inevitabil=
ity of death=2C the illusion and the reality of time.

[=E2=80=A6]

Working like this=2C and maintaining the fundamental attitude of sincerity=
 about yourself and your discoveries=2C you will become disillusioned not=
 only with your certainties=2C but with the structure of your mind itself.=
 You will realize that what you need is not new beliefs=2C new information=
=2C new theories=2C but an entirely new mind.

Such dissolution of certainty=2C Needleman argues=2C is the gateway to rea=
l freedom:

Real ideas open the mind to the heart=2C to the heart of the mind=2C to an=
other level of reality within ourselves=E2=80=A6 This is the taste=2C the=
 beginning=2C of inner freedom. Only fools imagine that freedom means gett=
ing what one happens to desire. Real freedom begins with obedience to a hi=
gher influence =E2=80=94 a higher=2C finer energy within oneself.

[=E2=80=A6]

What is higher in yourself? That way of thinking about the question is the=
 beginning of the answer =E2=80=94 because it involves a real idea which h=
as been handed down to humanity over thousands of years=E2=80=A6 At such a=
 point you yourself will find the answer =E2=80=94 not as a thought=2C but=
 as an experience.

You will for a moment become the answer! You will not only have a taste of=
 real freedom; you will for a moment be freedom.

How to cultivate such a capacity for self-erasure in the service of self-t=
ranscendence and self-liberation is what Needleman goes on to explore in t=
he remainder of the thoroughly elevating and illuminating I Am Not I (http=
://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1623170141/braipick-20?utm_source=3DBra=
in+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=
=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a1=
2b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Complement it with Aldous Huxley on the divine=
 within (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/22/aldous-huxley-who-are-we=
-divine-within/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAI=
L_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a=
0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C astrophysici=
st Marcelo Gleiser on how to live with mystery in the age of knowledge (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/02/the-island-of-knowledge-marcelo-gle=
iser/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN=
_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-=
236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and philosopher Amelie=
 Rorty on the seven layers of identity in literature and life (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2016/03/02/amelie-rorty-the-identities-of-persons/?utm_=
