** Walk Through Walls: Marina Abramovi=C4=87 on Art=2C Fear=2C Taking Risk=
s=2C and Pain as a Focal Lens for Presence (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/10/26/walk-through-walls-marina-abramovic/?utm_source=3DBrain+Picking=
s&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&u=
tm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1101905042/braipick-20?utm_source=
=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_=
medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=
=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CTo make use =E2=80=A6 of the sufferings that chance inflicts upon=
 us is better than inflicting discipline upon oneself=2C=E2=80=9D Simone W=
eil wrote in contemplating how to make use of our suffering (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2015/05/12/simone-weil-pain/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&=
utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm=
_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) shortly before her untimely=2C heroic death in 1942. Weil=2C=
 perhaps the closest thing we have to a modern secular saint=2C believed t=
hat approaching pain with consent rather than resistance was a creative ac=
t and a source of empowerment=2C subverting the given circumstances into o=
ne=E2=80=99s locus of agency.

In many ways=2C performance artist Marina Abramovi=C4=87 (b. November 30=
=2C 1946) has plotted her trailblazing creative trajectory along the same=
 vector of conviction=2C using pain =E2=80=94 both externally inflicted an=
d self-elected =E2=80=94 as a creative medium=2C but using discipline as t=
he mechanism of subversion. As she approaches her seventieth year=2C Abram=
ovi=C4=87 looks back on her unusual life in her magnificent memoir Walk Th=
rough Walls (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1101905042/braipick-20=
?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016=
_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-=
236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.wor=
ldcat.org/title/walk-through-walls-a-memoir/oclc/953164776&referer=3Dbrief=
_results?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPA=
IGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-=
236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ).

Marina=2C age 4=2C with her father

Abramovi=C4=87 writes unsentimentally about the trials and terrors of her=
 childhood in Yugoslavia =E2=80=94 about growing up in relative privilege=
 amid the soul-draining drabness of communism; about being =E2=80=9Cmateri=
ally comfortable but emotionally desolate=E2=80=9D; about the brutality of=
 her parents=E2=80=99 marriage=2C both of whom slept with loaded pistols o=
n their bedside tables; about the constant beatings by her mother=2C a one=
time army major with a steel hand and a steel heart=2C then director of th=
e formidably named Museum of Art and Revolution. (I was struck by the asto=
nishing number of parallels=2C both cultural and personal=2C between Abram=
ovi=C4=87=E2=80=99s early life and my own =E2=80=94 two lives lived a gene=
ration apart across the border of our neighboring countries.)

Marina=2C age 5=2C in Belgrade

=E2=80=9CThis was the happiest time of my childhood=2C=E2=80=9D Abramovi=
=C4=87 recounts of her yearlong stay in a hospital at age six=2C after a p=
ersistent nosebleed required that she sleep sitting up in order not to cho=
ke on her own blood. The doctors first suspected leukemia=2C but a litany=
 of tests revealed=2C as Abramovi=C4=87 puts it=2C =E2=80=9Csomething more=
 mysterious=E2=80=A6 some kind of psychosomatic reaction=E2=80=9D to her m=
other=E2=80=99s beatings. (We now know=2C of course=2C that there is nothi=
ng mysterious about such a reaction =E2=80=94 as pioneering immunologist E=
sther Sternberg would demonstrate three decades later=2C emotional stress=
 affects our susceptibility to physical illness (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2015/07/20/esther-sternberg-balance-within-stress-emotion/?utm_source=
=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_=
medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=
=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) in a variety of ways=2C including manife=
stations this dramatic.) After seven-year-old Marina was sent home from th=
e hospital=2C the beatings continued=2C with only slightly diminished freq=
uency and severity.

It was around that time that Abramovi=C4=87=2C like young Jane Goodall (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/19/me-jane-patrick-mcdonnell/?utm_sour=
ce=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&ut=
m_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=
=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C awakened to what would become her li=
felong purpose. She writes:

I knew from the age of six or seven that I wanted to be an artist. My moth=
er punished me for many things=2C but she encouraged me in this one way. A=
rt was holy to her.

[=E2=80=A6]

My first paintings were of my dreams. They were more real to me than the r=
eality I was living in =E2=80=94 I didn=E2=80=99t like my reality. I remem=
ber waking up=2C and the memory of my dreams was so strong that I would wr=
ite them down=2C and then I would paint them=2C in just two very particula=
r colors=2C a deep green and a night blue. Never anything else.

If fleshly brutality was the norm of her childhood=2C its specter haunted=
 Marina since before she was born =E2=80=94 she was named after a Russian=
 soldier with whom her father had been in love during WWII=2C blown up by=
 a grenade before his eyes. But there is something intensely enthralling a=
bout Abramovi=C4=87=E2=80=99s simple=2C matter-of-factly candor in surveyi=
ng=2C without belaboring=2C the traumatic formative experiences despite wh=
ich =E2=80=94 and=2C to a large extent=2C because of which =E2=80=94 she b=
ecame the person and artist she is.

Abramovi=C4=87=2C age 14=2C wearing clothes she had made from curtains

She recounts:

Deep shame=2C maximum self-consciousness. When I was young it was impossib=
le for me to talk to people. Now I can stand in front of three thousand pe=
ople without any notes=2C any preconception of what I=E2=80=99m going to s=
ay=2C even without visual material=2C and I can look at everyone in the au=
dience and talk for two hours easily.

What happened?

Art happened.

Abramovi=C4=87=2C age 15=2C Istria

Art became a life-straw for Abramovi=C4=87 =E2=80=94 a hedge against the l=
oneliness and sadness of her home life. Amid her mother=E2=80=99s suffocat=
ing and punishing control=2C art became the one domain where she felt she=
 had absolute freedom =E2=80=94 the freedom of expression.

Abramovi=C4=87=2C age 22=2C at her painting studio in Belgrade

At twenty-four=2C Abramovi=C4=87 was still living at home with her mother=
 =E2=80=94 not at all uncommon in Eastern Europe =E2=80=94 and still had t=
o abide by a 10pm curfew. But she immersed herself in art=2C painted obses=
sively=2C and was admitted into Belgrade=E2=80=99s Academy of Fine Arts. S=
he was the only woman in her art collective.

Abramovi=C4=87=2C age 24=2C with her art collective at Belgrade=E2=80=99s=
 Student Cultural Center

Together=2C they would spend hours talking about =E2=80=9Ca way past paint=
ing: a way to put life itself into art.=E2=80=9D This way became performan=
ce art=2C and Abramovi=C4=87 threw herself wholeheartedly=2C wholebodily i=
nto it. By her mid-twenties=2C she had made a name for herself in Belgrade=
=2E In 1972=2C a Scottish curator traversed the Iron Curtain in search of or=
iginal ideas for the famed Edinburgh Festival the following summer and was=
 captivated by her work. He invited Abramovi=C4=87 to show at the festival=
 =E2=80=94 an invitation into what was practically another world: the West=
=2E

Abramovi=C4=87 arrived in Edinburg thrilled and terrified in equal measure=
=2E She recalls:

It was my first trip to the West as an artist. I felt like a very small fi=
sh in a very big pond.

The piece she chose to perform=2C titled Rhythm 10=2C was a play on a drin=
king game popular among Russian and Yugoslav peasants: The player spreads=
 their fingers onto a wooden surface and=2C using a sharp knife=2C begins=
 rapidly stabbing the wood in the gap between the fingers. Whenever they m=
iss and knick or stab themselves=2C they take a shot; the more shots they=
 take=2C the more they lose control and cut themselves =E2=80=94 an expone=
ntially accelerating machine for self-inflicted pain. Abramovi=C4=87=E2=80=
=99s piece subverted this mechanism by placing the artist at the locus of=
 control =E2=80=94 she would go through the rapid motions deliberately=2C=
 using ten different knives in succession=2C so that whenever she stabbed=
 herself=2C the pain would be a testament to absolute presence.

In a sentiment that calls to mind Amanda Palmer=E2=80=99s assertion that=
 =E2=80=9Cwherever you don=E2=80=99t want to go=2C whatever that risk is=
=2C wherever the unsafe place is =E2=80=94 that really is the gift that yo=
u have to give=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/11/02/van-g=
ogh-fear-risk/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL=
_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0=
-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Abramovi=C4=87 re=
flects on her initiation into her own self as an artist:

Some big part of me is thrilled by the unknown=2C by the idea of taking ri=
sks. When it comes to doing risky things=2C I don=E2=80=99t care. I just g=
o for it.

That doesn=E2=80=99t mean I=E2=80=99m fearless. Quite the opposite. The id=
ea of death terrifies me. When there is turbulence on an airplane=2C I sha=
ke with fear. I start composing my last will and testament. But when it co=
mes to my work=2C I cast caution to the winds.

[=E2=80=A6]

I could hardly breathe from the idea that I was going to do this. But I wa=
s also serious about what I was about to do=2C 100 percent committed. I wa=
s so serious about everything then! Yet I think I needed this gravity. Muc=
h later on=2C I read a statement of Bruce Nauman=E2=80=99s: =E2=80=9CArt i=
s a matter of life and death.=E2=80=9D It sounds melodramatic=2C but it=E2=
=80=99s so true. This was exactly how it was for me=2C even at the beginni=
ng. Art was life and death. There was nothing else. It was so serious=2C a=
nd so necessary.

The determination that carried her through the performance embodies Nicole=
 Krauss=E2=80=99s beautiful assertion that =E2=80=9Cbravery is always more=
 intelligent than fear=2C since it is built on the foundation of what one=
 knows about oneself: the knowledge of one=E2=80=99s strength and capacity=
=2C of one=E2=80=99s passion.=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015=
/11/09/nicole-krauss-van-gogh-letter/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_camp=
aign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D=
0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) When she finished the piece=2C having gone through all ten knives=2C=
 Abramovi=C4=87 faced the white paper onto which she had performed it=2C=
 =E2=80=9Cstained very impressively=E2=80=9D with her own blood =E2=80=94=
 the very blood that had been one of her biggest fears during her violent=
 childhood. The self-harm was in a way self-healing. It was also her first=
 awareness of what art does =E2=80=94 its supreme power of self-transcende=
nce=2C for artist and viewer alike=2C and a powerful channel of communion=
 between the two. She writes:

The crowd stared=2C dead silent. And a very strange feeling came over me=
=2C something I had never dreamed of: It was as if electricity was running=
 through my body=2C and the audience and I had become one. A single organi=
sm. The sense of danger in the room had united the onlookers and me in tha=
t moment: the here and now=2C and nowhere else.

That thing that each of us lives with=2C that you are your own little self=
 privately =E2=80=94 once you step into the performance space=2C you are a=
cting from a higher self=2C and it=E2=80=99s not you anymore. It=E2=80=99s=
 not the you that you know. It=E2=80=99s something else. There on the gymn=
asium floor of Melville College in Edinburgh=2C Scotland=2C it was as if I=
 had become=2C at the same time=2C a receiver and transmitter of huge=2C T=
esla-like energy. The fear was gone=2C the pain was gone. I had become a M=
arina whom I didn=E2=80=99t know yet.

For Abramovi=C4=87=2C the experience was also a homecoming of sorts =E2=80=
=94 using pain as a focal point of presence=2C she had attained a taste of=
 that coveted freedom=2C the freedom of expression=2C which had first draw=
n her to art as a child. She reflects:

Listening to the wild applause from the audience=2C I knew I=E2=80=99d suc=
ceeded in creating an unprecedented unity of time present and time past wi=
th random errors.

I had experienced absolute freedom =E2=80=94 I had felt that my body was w=
ithout boundaries=2C limitless; that pain didn=E2=80=99t matter=2C that no=
thing mattered at all =E2=80=94 and it intoxicated me. I was drunk from th=
e overwhelming energy that I=E2=80=99d received. That was the moment I kne=
w that I had found my medium. No painting=2C no object that I could make=
=2C could ever give me that kind of feeling=2C and it was a feeling I knew=
 I would have to seek out=2C again and again and again.

Abramovi=C4=87 performing Art Must Be Beautiful=2C Artist Must Be Beautifu=
l=2C 1975

But beyond the personal transcendence=2C Abramovi=C4=87 approached her art=
 as a gateway into the largest=2C most universal questions of meaning in h=
uman life. Looking back on a piece she performed at Copenhagen=E2=80=99s C=
harlottenborg Art Festival two years later=2C titled Art Must Be Beautiful=
=2C Artist Must Be Beautiful =E2=80=94 an ironic response to the communist=
-era =E2=80=9Caesthetic presumption that art must be beautiful=E2=80=9D an=
d a revolt against the notion of art as vacant decoration =E2=80=94 Abramo=
vi=C4=87 writes:

When it came to art=2C I only cared about content: what a work meant=E2=80=
=A6 I had come to believe that art must be disturbing=2C art must ask ques=
tions=2C art must predict the future. If art is just political=2C it becom=
es like newspaper. It can be used once=2C and the next day it=E2=80=99s ye=
sterday=E2=80=99s news. Only layers of meaning can give long life to art=
 =E2=80=94 that way=2C society takes what it needs from the work over time=
=2E

This view of art =E2=80=94 as a source of meaning=2C as a transmutation of=
 pain into power=2C as a sublime medium of human connection through mutual=
 vulnerability =E2=80=94 would animate Abramovi=C4=87=E2=80=99s long and i=
llustrious career. Thirty-five years after that initial knife-point revela=
tion=2C she would experience the same sublime unity of spacetime in one of=
 her most celebrated works=2C The Artist Is Present =E2=80=94 an astonishi=
ng feat of body=2C spirit=2C and creative vitality=2C in which Abramovi=C4=
=87 spent 736 hours sitting at a table on the second floor of the Museum o=
f Modern Art=2C in intense silence=2C as visitors ranging from children to=
 public figures to the great love of her youth=2C the artist Ulay=2C sat a=
cross from her and shared communion in crystalline presence.

Abramovi=C4=87=2C The Artist Is Present=2C 2010. Sitting across from her=
=2C Ulay. (Photograph: Scott Rudd (http://scottruddphotography.com?utm_sou=
rce=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&u=
tm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_ci=
d=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )

She reflects on how the project illuminated for her the meaning of art and=
 its ultimate purpose:

During the final month=2C as this piece became one with life itself=2C I s=
tarted to think intensely about the purpose of my existence. Eight hundred=
 fifty thousand people in all had stood in the atrium=2C seventeen thousan=
d on the final day alone. And I was there for everyone there=2C whether th=
ey sat with me or not. Suddenly=2C out of nowhere in the world=2C this ove=
rwhelming need had appeared. The responsibility was enormous.

I was there for everyone who was there. A great trust had been given to me=
 =E2=80=94 a trust that I didn=E2=80=99t dare abuse=2C in any way. Hearts=
 were opened to me=2C and I opened my heart in return=2C time after time a=
fter time. I opened my heart to each one=2C then closed my eyes =E2=80=94=
 and then there was always another. My physical pain was one thing. But th=
e pain in my heart=2C the pain of pure love=2C was far greater.

[=E2=80=A6]

The sheer quantity of love=2C the unconditional love of total strangers=2C=
 was the most incredible feeling I=E2=80=99ve ever had. I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow if this is art=2C I said to myself. I don=E2=80=99t know what this is=
=2C or what art is. I=E2=80=99d always thought of art as something that wa=
s expressed through certain tools: painting=2C sculpture=2C photography=2C=
 writing=2C film=2C music=2C architecture. And yes=2C performance. But thi=
s performance went beyond performance. This was life. Could art=2C should=
 art=2C be isolated from life? I began to feel more and more strongly that=
 art must be life =E2=80=94 it must belong to everybody. I felt=2C more po=
werfully than ever=2C that what I had created had a purpose.

In the remainder of the thoroughly terrific Walk Through Walls (http://www=
=2Eamazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1101905042/braipick-20?utm_source=3DBrain+Pic=
kings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Dema=
il&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Abramovi=C4=87 goes on to chronicle how the peculi=
ar fragments of her life =E2=80=94 her traumatic but eventually reconcilia=
tory relationship with her mother=2C her cinematic twelve-year romance wit=
h Ulay=2C her survival of both poverty and privilege =E2=80=94 converged i=
nto this mosaic of creative purpose. Complement it with some of the greate=
st artists of our time=2C including Abramovi=C4=87 herself=2C on courage=
=2C creativity=2C criticism=2C and what success really means (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2015/01/12/33-artists-in-3-acts-thornton/?utm_source=3DB=
rain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073=
a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Van Gogh on fear=2C risk-taki=
ng=2C and how inspired mistakes move us forward (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2015/11/02/van-gogh-fear-risk/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campai=
gn=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_=
179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
