In the fall of 1946=2C a South African little girl aspiring to be a scient=
ist wrote to Einstein (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/04/09/dear-profe=
ssor-einstein-girl/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-=
EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a1=
2b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and ended he=
r letter with a self-conscious entreatment: =E2=80=9CI hope you will not t=
hink any the less of me for being a girl!=E2=80=9D Einstein responded with=
 words of assuring wisdom that resonate to this day: =E2=80=9CI do not min=
d that you are a girl=2C but the main thing is that you yourself do not mi=
nd. There is no reason for it.=E2=80=9D

And yet reasons don=E2=80=99t always come from reason. The history of scie=
nce=2C like the history of the world itself=2C is the history of unreasona=
ble asymmetries of power=2C the suppressive consequences of which have mea=
nt that the comparatively few women (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07=
/28/women-in-science-rachel-ignotofsky/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_ca=
mpaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=
=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) who rose to the top of their respective field did so due to inord=
inate brilliance and tenacity.

Among the most outstanding yet under-celebrated of these pioneering women=
 is the Austrian physicist Lise Meitner (November 7=2C 1878=E2=80=93Octobe=
r 27=2C 1968)=2C who led the team that discovered nuclear fission but was=
 excluded from the Nobel Prize for the discovery=2C and whose story I firs=
t encountered in Alan Lightman=E2=80=99s illuminating 1990 book The Discov=
eries (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0375421688/braipick-20?utm_s=
ource=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29=
&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_=
cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . This diminutive Jewish woman=2C who=
 had barely saved her own life from the Nazis=2C was heralded by Einstein=
 as the Marie Curie of the German-speaking world. She is the subject of th=
e excellent biography Lise Meitner: A Life in Physics (http://www.amazon.c=
om/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520208609/braipick-20?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm=
_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_te=
rm=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/lise-meitner-a-l=
ife-in-physics/oclc/32893857&referer=3Dbrief_results?utm_source=3DBrain+Pi=
ckings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Dem=
ail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) by chemist=2C science historian=2C and Guggenheim f=
ellow Ruth Lewin Sime.

Lise Meitner=2C 1906

Meitner was born in Vienna a little more than a year after pioneering astr=
onomer Maria Mitchell=2C who paved the way for women in science (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2013/08/22/maria-mitchell-education-women-in-science/=
?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016=
_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-=
236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) across the Atlantic=2C admonish=
ed the first class of female astronomers: =E2=80=9CNo woman should say=2C=
 =E2=80=98I am but a woman!=E2=80=99 But a woman! What more can you ask to=
 be?=E2=80=9D Although Meitner showed a gift for mathematics from an early=
 age=2C there was little correlation between aptitude and opportunity for=
 women in 19th-century Europe. At the end of her long life=2C she would re=
count=2C not bitterly but wistfully:

Thinking back to =E2=80=A6 the time of my youth=2C one realizes with some=
 astonishment how many problems then existed in the lives of ordinary youn=
g girls=2C which now seem almost unimaginable. Among the most difficult of=
 these problems was the possibility of normal intellectual training.

Sime herself=2C who spent decades as the only woman at her university depa=
rtment=2C captures the broader cultural necessity of telling Meitner=E2=80=
=99s story: =E2=80=9CI was known as the woman the all-male chemistry depar=
tment did not want to hire; under such circumstances one becomes=2C and re=
mains=2C a feminist.=E2=80=9D She writes of Meitner=E2=80=99s Sisyphean ri=
se to stature:

Her schooling in Vienna ended when she was fourteen=2C but a few years lat=
er=2C the university admitted women=2C and she studied physics under the c=
harismatic Ludwig Boltzmann. As a young woman she went to Berlin without t=
he slightest prospects for a future in physics=2C but again she was fortun=
ate=2C finding a mentor and friend in Max Planck and a collaborator in Ott=
o Hahn=2C a chemist just her age. Together Meitner and Hahn made names for=
 themselves in radioactivity=2C and then in the 1920s Meitner went on=2C i=
ndependent of Hahn=2C into nuclear physics=2C an emerging field in which s=
he was a pioneer. In the Berlin physics community she was=2C as Einstein l=
iked to say=2C =E2=80=9Cour Marie Curie=E2=80=9D; among physicists everywh=
ere=2C she was regarded as one of the great experimentalists of her day=E2=
=80=A6 The painfully shy young woman had become an assertive professor =E2=
=80=94 =E2=80=9Cshort=2C dark=2C and bossy=2C=E2=80=9D her nephew would te=
ase =E2=80=94 and although at times she was haunted by the insecurity of h=
er youth=2C she never doubted that
physics was worth it.

Illustration of Lise Meitner from Women in Science: 50 Fearless Pioneers W=
ho Changed the World (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/28/women-in-sc=
ience-rachel-ignotofsky/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12=
b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-=
073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Rach=
el Ignotofsky

Meitner never married nor had children and=2C as far as her personal paper=
s indicate=2C never had a serious romance. But her life was a full one=2C=
 warmed by deep human connection =E2=80=94 she was an exceptionally devote=
d friend and surrounded herself with people she cherished=2C in Meitner=E2=
=80=99s own words=2C as =E2=80=9Cgreat and lovable personalities=E2=80=9D=
 who provided a =E2=80=9Cmagic musical accompaniment=E2=80=9D to her life.=
 Above all=2C she was besotted with science =E2=80=94 so much so that she=
 patiently chipped away at and eventually broke through every imaginable o=
bstruction to pursuing her passion.

Since her formal schooling had ended at the age of fourteen=2C Meitner spe=
nt a few years repressing her scientific ambitions. But they burned in her=
 with irrepressible ardor. Finally=2C when Austrian universities began adm=
itting women in 1901=2C she obtained her high school certification at the=
 age of twenty-three after compressing eight years=E2=80=99 worth of logic=
=2C literature=2C mathematics=2C Greek=2C Latin=2C botany=2C zoology=2C an=
d physics into twenty months of study in order to take the examination tha=
t would qualify her for university. She received her Ph.D. in 1905=2C one=
 of a handful of women in the world to have achieved a doctorate in physic=
s by that point.

But when 29-year-old Meitner traveled to Berlin=2C hoping to study with th=
e great Max Planck=2C she seemed to have entered a time machine =E2=80=94=
 German universities still had their doors firmly shut to women. She had t=
o ask for a special permission to attend Planck=E2=80=99s lectures.

In the fall of 1907=2C she met Otto Hahn =E2=80=94 a German chemist four m=
onths her junior=2C as interested in radioactivity as she was=2C and unopp=
osed to working with women. But women were forbidden from entering=2C much=
 less working at=2C Berlin=E2=80=99s Chemical Institute=2C so in order to=
 collaborate=2C Meitner and Hahn had to work in a former carpentry shop co=
nverted into a lab in the basement of the building. Hahn was allowed to cl=
imb up the floors=2C but Meitner was not =E2=80=94 a hard fact that fringe=
s on metaphor.

Meitner and Hahn in their basement laboratory=2C 1913

The two scientists filled each other=E2=80=99s gaps with their respective=
 aptitudes =E2=80=94 Meitner=2C trained in physics=2C was a brilliant math=
ematician who thought conceptually and could design highly original experi=
ments to test her ideas; Hahn=2C trained in chemistry=2C excelled at punct=
ilious lab work. Over the thirty years they collaborated=2C Meitner and Ha=
hn emerged as pioneers in the study of radioactivity. Eventually=2C Meitne=
r gained independence from Hahn =E2=80=94 she published fifty-six papers o=
n her own between 1921 and 1934.

But as her career was taking off=2C the Nazis began usurping Europe. Meitn=
er and Hahn=E2=80=99s third collaborator=2C a junior scientist named Fritz=
 Strassmann=2C had already gotten in trouble for refusing to join Nazi org=
anizations. In 1938=2C just as the three scientists were performing their=
 most visionary experiments=2C Nazi troops marched into Austria. Meitner r=
efused to hide her Jewish heritage. Her only remaining option was to leave=
=2C but the Nazis had already put anti-Semitic laws in place prohibiting u=
niversity professors from exiting the country. On July 13=2C with the help=
 of Hahn and a few other scientist friends=2C Meitner made a narrow escape=
 across the Dutch border. From Holland=2C she migrated to Denmark=2C where=
 she stayed with her friend Niels Bohr. She finally found a permanent home=
 at the Nobel Institute for Physics in Sweden. (Three centuries earlier=2C=
 Descartes=2C supreme champion of reason (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
16/03/31/descartes-rules-for-the-direction-of-the-mind/?utm_source=3DBrain=
+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=
=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a1=
2b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C
had also fled to Sweden to avoid the Inquisition after witnessing the tria=
l of Galileo (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/02/15/galileo-letter-to-d=
uchess-of-tuscany/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-E=
MAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12=
b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .)

Lise Meitner shortly before her exile

That November=2C Hahn and Meitner met secretly in Copenhagen to discuss so=
me perplexing results Hahn and Strassmann had obtained: After bombarding t=
he nucleus of a uranium atom (atomic number 92) with a single neutron=2C t=
hey had ended up with the nucleus of radium (atomic number 88) =E2=80=94 a=
 seemingly magical transmutation that didn=E2=80=99t make physical sense.=
 That a tiny neutron moving at low speed would destabilize and downright s=
hatter something as robust as an atom=2C knocking down its atomic number i=
nto a wholly different element=2C seemed as mythic as David taking out Gol=
iath with a slingshot.

At that point=2C Hahn was one of the world=E2=80=99s best radiochemists an=
d Meitner one of the world=E2=80=99s best physicists. She told him unequiv=
ocally that his chemical reaction made no sense on physical grounds and ur=
ged him to repeat the experiment.

Meitner herself continued to ponder the perplexity. The epiphany arrived o=
n Christmas day=2C during a walk with her nephew and collaborator=2C Otto=
 Robert Frisch. In recounting the occasion in his memoir=2C Frisch would i=
nadvertently provide the most perfect metaphor for how women make progress=
 in science relative to their male peers:

We walked up and down in the snow=2C I on skis and she on foot (she said a=
nd proved that she could get along just as fast that way).

In making sense of the nonsensical results=2C Meitner and Frisch came up w=
ith what they would call nuclear fission =E2=80=94 a word used for the ver=
y first time in the seventh paragraph of the paper they published the foll=
owing month. The notion that a nucleus can split and be transformed into a=
nother element was radical =E2=80=94 no one had fathomed it before. Meitne=
r had provided the first understanding of how and why this happened.

Illustration from Our Friend the Atom (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/=
02/18/our-friend-the-atom-disney/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=
=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_17=
9ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) =2C a 1956 Disney primer on nuclear energy

Nuclear fission would prove to be one of the most powerful =E2=80=94 and d=
angerous =E2=80=94 discoveries in the history humanity=2C a power that suc=
cumbed to our dual capacities for good and evil: It was central to the inv=
ention of the deadliest weapon in human history=2C the atomic bomb. In fac=
t=2C later in life Meitner was cruelly referred to as =E2=80=9Cthe Jewish=
 mother of the atomic bomb=2C=E2=80=9D even though her discovery was purel=
y scientific=2C it predated this malevolent application by many years=2C a=
nd once she saw it put into practice to destructive ends=2C she adamantly=
 refused to work on the bomb. She=2C like the rest of the world=2C saw the=
 bomb as a grave turning point for humanity. Years later=2C she would issu=
e a bittersweet lamentation for the era that ended with its invention:

One could love one=E2=80=99s work and not always be tormented by the fear=
 of the ghastly and malevolent thins that people might do with beautiful s=
cientific findings.

The discovery of fission itself was a supreme example of these beautiful s=
cientific findings =E2=80=94 a triumph of the human intellect over the mys=
teries of nature=2C as well as a testament to interpretation as a creative=
 act. The nonsensical empirical results were Hahn=E2=80=99s=2C but what ex=
tracted meaning from them was Meitner=E2=80=99s interpretation =E2=80=94 s=
he had dis-covered=2C in the proper sense of uncovering something obscured=
 from view=2C the underlying principle that made sense of the grand perple=
xity.

Hahn took her groundbreaking insight and ran with it=2C publishing the dis=
covery without mentioning her name. It is beside the point whether his rea=
sons were personal jealousies or the political cowardice of incensing the=
 Nazi authorities =E2=80=94 the point is that Meitner felt deeply betrayed=
 by the injustice. She wrote to her brother Walter:

I have no self confidence=E2=80=A6 Hahn has just published absolutely wond=
erful things based on our work together =E2=80=A6 much as these results ma=
ke me happy for Hahn=2C both personally and scientifically=2C many people=
 here must think I contributed absolutely nothing to it =E2=80=94 and now=
 I am so discouraged.

Lise Meitner at age 50

In 1944=2C the discovery of nuclear fission was awarded the Nobel Prize in=
 Chemistry =E2=80=94 to Hahn alone. Sime writes:

The distortion of reality and the suppression of memory are recurrent them=
es in any study of Nazi Germany and its aftermath. By any normal standard=
 of scientific attribution=2C there would have been no doubt about Meitner=
=E2=80=99s role in the discovery of fission. For it is clear from the publ=
ished record and from private correspondence that this was a discovery to=
 which Meitner contributed from beginning to end =E2=80=94 an inherently i=
nterdisciplinary discovery that would=2C without question=2C have been rec=
ognized as such=2C were it not for the artifact of Meitner=E2=80=99s force=
d emigration. But nothing about this discovery was untouched by the politi=
cs of Germany in 1938. The same racial policies that drove Meitner out of=
 Germany made it impossible for her to be part of Hahn and Strassmann=E2=
=80=99s publication=2C and dangerous for Hahn to acknowledge their continu=
ing ties. A few weeks after the discovery was made=2C Hahn claimed it for=
 chemistry alone; before long=2C he suppressed and denied not only his hid=
den
collaboration with a =E2=80=9Cnon-Aryan=E2=80=9D in exile but the value of=
 nearly everything she had done before as well. It was self-deception=2C b=
rought on by fear. Hahn=E2=80=99s dishonesty distorted the record of this=
 discovery and almost cost Lise Meitner her place in its history.

Meitner received countless accolades in her lifetime and even had a chemic=
al element=2C meitnerium=2C posthumously named after her=2C but the slight=
 was never righted. Although every imaginable roadblock had been placed be=
fore her in pursuing a scientific education=2C she had survived Nazi perse=
cution=2C and had endured the anguish of exile=2C she considered the Nobel=
 omission that most irredeemable sorrow of her life.

Sime writes:

Except for a few brief statements=2C she did not campaign on her own behal=
f; she did not write an autobiography=2C nor did she authorize a biography=
 during her lifetime. Only seldom did she speak of her struggle for educat=
ion and acceptance=2C although the insecurity and isolation of her formati=
ve years affected her deeply later on. And she almost never spoke of her f=
orced emigration=2C shattered career=2C or broken friendships. She would h=
ave preferred that the essentials of her life be gleaned from her scientif=
ic publications=2C but she knew that in her case that would not suffice.

[=E2=80=A6]

Scientist that she was=2C she preserved her data. Her rich collection of p=
ersonal papers=2C in addition to archival material from other sources=2C p=
rovides the basis for a detailed understanding of her work=2C her life=2C=
 and the exceptionally difficult period in which she lived.

Sime considers the more systemic implications of Meitner=E2=80=99s case:

To insist that Meitner contributed nothing to the fission discovery=2C to=
 imply that Meitner and Frisch had been given an unfair advantage =E2=80=
=94 these were ways of denying that she had been treated unjustly and=2C i=
n a larger sense=2C of refusing to confront the injustice and crimes of th=
e Nazi period. Rather than acknowledging that Meitner=E2=80=99s exclusion=
 from fission was political=2C Hahn and his hangers-on invented spurious s=
cientific reasons for it. Arrogantly=2C and with misplaced national pride=
=2C they denied the injustice=2C created new injustice =E2=80=94 and impli=
cated themselves.

Given the echo chamber of interpretive opinion we call history=2C Hahn=E2=
=80=99s view was readily echoed by his followers and=2C in turn=2C by gene=
rations of journalists and uncritical commentators on the history of scien=
ce. The Nobel exclusion was the most obvious=2C but the egregious erasure=
 of Meitner=E2=80=99s legacy didn=E2=80=99t end there. The fission apparat=
us =E2=80=94 the very instrument she had used in her Berlin laboratory to=
 make her discoveries =E2=80=94 was on display at Germany=E2=80=99s premie=
re science museum for thirty-five years without so much as mentioning her=
 name.

This=2C of course=2C was far from the last time that a woman was excluded=
 from a Nobel Prize for a discovery she either made or made possible with=
 her significant contribution: There is=2C perhaps most famously=2C Jocely=
n Bell Burnell=E2=80=99s discovery of pulsars (https://www.brainpickings.o=
rg/2016/07/15/jocelyn-bell-burnell-pulsar-nobel/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickin=
gs&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&=
utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C to say nothing of Vera Rubin=2C whose confirmation of=
 the existence of dark matter (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/18/ve=
ra-rubin-interview-women-in-science/?utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campa=
ign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0=
_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) furnished a major leap in our understanding of the universe and yet r=
emains=2C decades later=2C bereft of a Nobel. But as physicist and novelis=
t Janna Levin wrote in her excellent NPR op-ed (http://www.npr.org/section=
s/13.7/2016/10/06/496657435/on-waiting-for-a-nobel-prize-announcement?utm_=
source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_2=
9&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc=
_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) about the foibles of scientific accl=
aim=2C =E2=80=9Cscientists do not devote their lives to the sometimes lone=
ly=2C agonizing=2C toilsome investigation of an austere universe because t=
hey want a prize.=E2=80=9D

Meitner herself articulated the same sentiment in a speech she gave in Vie=
nna at the age of 75:

Science makes people reach selflessly for truth and objectivity; it teache=
s people to accept reality=2C with wonder and admiration=2C not to mention=
 the deep joy and awe that the natural order of things brings to the true=
 scientist.

Lise Meitner late in life (Photograph: Sara Darling)

Meitner died peacefully in her sleep on October 27=2C 1968=2C days before=
 her ninetieth birthday. Otto Robert=2C one of her dearest friends=2C chos=
e the inscription for her headstone:

Lise Meitner: a physicist who never lost her humanity.

Complement the intensely interesting and important Lise Meitner: A Life in=
 Physics (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520208609/braipick-20?ut=
m_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10=
_29&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&=
mc_cid=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with pioneering astrophysicist Ver=
a Rubin on what it=E2=80=99s like to be a woman in science (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2016/04/18/vera-rubin-interview-women-in-science/?utm_sour=
ce=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_10_29&ut=
m_medium=3Demail&utm_term=3D0_179ffa2629-073a12b4a0-236831249&mc_cid=
=3D073a12b4a0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Margot Lee Shetterly on the untold s=
tory of the black women mathematicians who powered space exploration (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/hidden-figures-margot-lee-shetterly/?=
utm_source=3DBrain+Pickings&utm_campaign=3D073a12b4a0-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2016_=
