line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Sime considers the more systemic impl=
ications of Meitner=E2=80=99s case:</p><blockquote style=3D"-webkit-text-s=
ize-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;display: block;-webkit-margin-=
before: 0;-webkit-margin-after: 0;-webkit-margin-start: 40px;-webkit-margi=
n-end: 0px;"><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adju=
st: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;l=
ine-height: 170%;text-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp.=
com/13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1/images/2e292385-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec.=
png" align=3D"left" style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;hei=
ght: auto;line-height: 100%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding: 5=
px 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px!important;">To insist that Me=
itner contributed nothing to the fission discovery=2C to imply that Meitne=
r and Frisch had been given an unfair advantage =E2=80=94 these were ways=
 of denying that she had been treated unjustly and=2C in a larger sense=2C=
 of refusing to confront the injustice and crimes of the Nazi period. Rath=
er than acknowledging that Meitner=E2=80=99s exclusion from fission was po=
litical=2C Hahn and his hangers-on invented spurious scientific reasons fo=
r it. Arrogantly=2C and with misplaced national pride=2C they denied the i=
njustice=2C created new injustice =E2=80=94 and implicated themselves.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adju=
st: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line=
-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Given the echo chamber of interpretive op=
inion we call history=2C Hahn=E2=80=99s view was readily echoed by his fol=
lowers and=2C in turn=2C by generations of journalists and uncritical comm=
entators on the history of science. The Nobel exclusion was the most obvio=
us=2C but the egregious erasure of Meitner=E2=80=99s legacy didn=E2=80=99t=
 end there. The fission apparatus =E2=80=94 the very instrument she had us=
ed in her Berlin laboratory to make her discoveries =E2=80=94 was on displ=
ay at Germany=E2=80=99s premiere science museum for thirty-five years with=
out so much as mentioning her name. </p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adju=
st: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C=
 serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">This=2C of cou=
rse=2C was far from the last time that a woman was excluded from a Nobel P=
rize for a discovery she either made or made possible with her significant=
 contribution: There is=2C perhaps most famously=2C Jocelyn Bell Burnell=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage.com/track/click=
?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3De4b51a6169&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-=
webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;te=
xt-decoration: underline;">discovery of pulsars</a>=2C to say nothing of V=
era Rubin=2C whose <a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage1.com/tr=
ack/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D66223cd038&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" s=
tyle=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #=
C33737;text-decoration: underline;">confirmation of the existence of dark=
 matter</a> furnished a major leap in our understanding of the universe an=
d yet remains=2C decades later=2C bereft of a Nobel. But as physicist and=
 novelist Janna Levin wrote in her excellent <a href=3D"http://brainpickin=
gs.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D1bbc=
93656a&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-s=
ize-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;text-decoration: underline;">NPR op-ed</a>=
 about the foibles of scientific acclaim=2C =E2=80=9Cscientists do not dev=
ote their lives to the sometimes lonely=2C agonizing=2C toilsome investiga=
tion of an austere universe because they want a prize.=E2=80=9D</p><p styl=
e=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262=
626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-a=
lign: left;">Meitner herself articulated the same sentiment in a speech sh=
e gave in Vienna at the age of 75:</p><blockquote style=3D"-webkit-text-si=
ze-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;display: block;-webkit-margin-b=
efore: 0;-webkit-margin-after: 0;-webkit-margin-start: 40px;-webkit-margin=
-end: 0px;"><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjus=
t: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;li=
ne-height: 170%;text-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp.c=
om/13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1/images/2e292385-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec.p=
ng" align=3D"left" style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;heig=
ht: auto;line-height: 100%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding: 5p=
x 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px!important;">Science makes peop=
le reach selflessly for truth and objectivity; it teaches people to accept=
 reality=2C with wonder and admiration=2C not to mention the deep joy and=
 awe that the natural order of things brings to the true scientist.</p></b=
lockquote><img src=3D"https://i0.wp.com/www.brainpickings.org/wp-content/u=
ploads/2016/10/LiseMeitner_SaraDarling.jpg?resize=3D680%2C827" style=3D"-m=
s-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;line-height: 100%;out=
